threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 64-bit LSB executable, x86-64, version 1 (SYSV), statically linked, stripped

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: This binary is a malicious Mirai-style botnet variant, likely Satori or Okiru, targeting Linux-based IoT devices and routers. It features automated exploitation of known vulnerabilities (Huawei HG532 via /ctrlt/DeviceUpgrade_1 and Realtek UPnP via /picsdesc.xml), telnet brute-forcing, and multiple DDoS attack vectors (SYN, ACK, and UDP floods). It includes a process-killing routine (sub_401997) to eliminate competing malware on the infected host. The sample communicates with a hardcoded C2/staging server at 104.168.101.27 to report successful infections and receive commands. Key IOCs include the C2 IP 104.168.101.27, exploitation strings like 'HUAWEIUPNP' and 'selfrep.realtek', and the 'Resentual Got You!' banner found in the main loop.
